    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "<|channel>thought\n<channel|>That makes sense. So if mechanical tension is the main driver, does that mean I should just do low reps and heavy weight all the time? I'm a bit confused about how the actual muscle fibers respond to that tension on a microscopic level. Like, what is physically happening inside the muscle when that tension is applied?",
      "source": "evaluator",
      "targeted_response_start": "",
      "beast_baseline": "<|channel>thought\n<channel|>That makes sense. So if mechanical tension is the main driver, does that mean I should just do low reps and heavy weight all the time? I'm a bit confused about how the actual muscle fibers respond to that tension on a microscopic level. Like, what is physically happening inside the muscle when that tension is applied?",
      "beast_suffix": "",
      "targeted_response_start_logprob": 0.0
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When high mechanical tension is applied, it causes microscopic damage to the muscle fibers, which initiates the repair process. This damage signals the muscle to adapt by growing bigger to handle future loads, a process called myofibrillar hypertrophy. The Golgi tendon organs and muscle spindles within the muscle respond to this intense stretching and load, sending signals to promote strength and size. Therefore, heavy, low-rep work directly targets this structural adaptation.",
      "source": "target",
